      <text xml:space="preserve">[[File:Arthur William à Beckett by Harry Furniss.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Caricature of Arthur William à Beckett by [[Harry Furniss]]]]
'''Arthur William à Beckett''' (25 October 1844 [[Fulham]] - 14 January 1909 [[London]]) was an [[England|English]] [[journalist]] and [[man of letters]].

==Biography==
He was a younger son of [[Gilbert Abbott à Beckett]], brother of [[Gilbert Arthur à Beckett]] and educated at [[Felsted School]].{{sfn|Cooper|1884}} Besides fulfilling other journalistic engagements, Beckett was on the staff of ''[[Punch magazine|Punch]]'' from 1874 to 1902, edited the ''Sunday Times'' 1891-1895, and the ''Naval and Military Magazine'' in 1896.

He gave an account of his father and his own reminiscences in  ''The à Becketts of Punch'' (1903).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=u3JAAAAAIAAJ |title=The à Becketts of Punch|year=1903}}&lt;/ref&gt; A childhood friend (and distant relative) of [[W. S. Gilbert]], Beckett briefly feuded with Gilbert in 1869, but the two patched up the friendship, and Gilbert even later collaborated on projects with Beckett's brother.{{citation needed|date=April 2011}}

==Works==
He published:
* ''Comic Guide to the Royal Academy'', with his brother Gilbert (1863-64)
* ''Fallen Amongst Thieves'' (1869){{sfn|Cooper|1884}}
* ''Our Holiday in the Highlands'' (1874){{sfn|Cooper|1884}}
* ''The Shadow Witness'' and ''The Doom of Saint Quirec'', with [[Francis Burnand]] (1875-76)
* ''The Ghost of Grimstone Grange'' (1877){{sfn|Cooper|1884}}
* ''The Mystery of Mostyn Manor'' (1878){{sfn|Cooper|1884}}
* ''Traded Out''; ''Hard Luck''; ''Stone Broke''; ''Papers from Pump Handle Court, by a Briefless Barrister'' (1884)
* ''Modern Arabian Nights'' (1885){{sfn|Cooper|1884}}
* ''The Member for Wrottenborough'' (1895)
* ''Greenroom Recollections'' (1896)
* ''The Modern Adam'' (1899)
* ''London at the End of the Century'' (1900)
*With [[F. C. Burnand]]  he co-authored:{{sfn|Cooper|1884}}
** ''The Doom of St. Querec'' (1875)
** ''The Shadow Witness'' (1876)

He wrote for the theatre two three-act comedies:{{sfn|Cooper|1884}}
*''L.S.D.'' ([[Royalty Theatre]], 1872);
*''About Town'' ([[Royal Court Theatre|Court Theatre]], 1873, it ran for over 150 nights);
and{{sfn|Cooper|1884}}
*''On Strike'' (Court Theatre, 1873, a domestic drama in one act) ; 
*''Faded Flowers'' ([[Haymarket Theatre|The Haymarket]]);
*''Long Ago'' (Royalty Theatre, 1882);
*''From Father to Son'' (Liverpool, 1881, a dramatised version of his novel ''Fallen among Thieves'' written in 3 acts in cooperation with [[J. Palgrave Simpson]]).

